nah, internet has actually brought a lot of problems to people
it presents an endless encyclopedia across a myriad of sites (though traffic has been oligopolized for years now), but it doesn't present you any way to discern things from what is interesting, what is useful and what is bollocks (unless you know how to search for these things, and most people really don't), at the same time it gilds itself with an aura of legitimacy by any means, so long as it catches on (sites/channels/etc that have earned their good repute by curating their content properly, or some bullshit ponzi scheme that gains traction because "it's a secret and you hit jackpot!!", etc)
in the end, it doesn't teach anyone how to discriminate information, primarily, while alienating those who can't (or don't know how to, or don't give a shit to) learn how, and that's how ignorance is still aplenty

Generally speaking, you begin rooting for a team long before you are old enough to even know what sports is. The father figure has much to do with this, but so does the family at large -- Uncles, cousins, grandparents, etc. Sometimes that dynamic results in a rebellious choice, ie - Clash with your father, therefore choose to be a fan of the other team in the city.

There are the establishment teams, the old New York -- Giants, Yankees, Rangers. And then there are the newer teams -- Jets, Mets, and Islanders. Fans tend to be Giants and Yankees and Rangers fans, or Jets and Mets and Islanders fans. There are of course variations but they are rare. Thus, becoming a fan of, let's say the Yankees, leads to friendships and discussions with fellow Yankees fans, which inevitably leads to discussion of the Giants and Rangers, which oftentimes has the effect of creating an interest in those teams. So you have the method by which new Giants-Yankees-Rangers fans are generated.

And, as always, there is the effect of success which translates to coverage by the local media. If one happens to grow up in a time when a particular team is having some success, there is an increased likelihood that the team and players will be seen more often on television and talked about more often by the local population. A young New Yorker might be in grammar school and hear much talk from his friends about the latest success of a particular team. Young people tend to be bandwagon fans. Such entry into sports is not at all uncommon. At home, parents and other family who are, let's say Mets fans, will talk more often about the Mets when the Mets are doing well, and not talk much about the Mets when the Mets are doing poorly. A young New Yorker might become interested in whatever team he hears mentioned more often. Success breeds new young fans. A team with more success tends to breed more fans.

>>128928074
Its a programming thing, money is stored in the program as a signed 32 bit integer which means the highest value possible is (2^31) - 1 or a little over 2.147 billion if they made the simple change of storing money as a 64 bit signed integer the highest possible value would be (2^63) -1.
Although the reason they possibly don't change this is because the number a 64 bit integer can hold is so large no one would feasibly get that much money and 64 bit integers will take up more space in the program doubling the amount of space required to store the amount of money each team has. Although with modern systems it wouldn't matter SI target shitty laptops with their game.

>>129012185
i did a save with england, germany, spain, italy, portugal, brazil, argentina loaded, and left the detail level at the default setting. after 15 years, the teams from the top 5 leagues dominated forever. the champions league, europa league, and conference league is always won by a team from one of those leagues. there is very little variance even at the group stage level of competitions. maybe you see like psv instead of anderlecht make it to the r16 one season. but by the time it gets to the quarter finals its only going to be teams from the big5 leagues, maybe benfica or porto sneak in.

i tried a different save with 15+ euro countrys loaded, and changed the detail level to "all competitive matches" just for the top leagues. there is still little variance, and the teams from the top 5 leagues do still dominate the continental competition, but i did begin to see a bit of variance at the group stage and 1st knockout rounds, especially in the europa and conference leagues. mainly with teams from the leagues i had loaded.

the main thing is that by loading the other leagues, it actually gives those teams a schedule and players. when it is an unloaded league, you end up playing against a team of grey players who have no scheduled games other than the continental competition. the grey "fake" players the game gives these teams, especially in smaller countrys with lower reputation, are absolutely terrible. i wouldnt be surprised if a loaded championship, segunda division, ligue2, serieb team would destroy an unloaded greyed out anderlecht or basel or shakhtar or other good team from a smaller country.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>Does Frida perform worse in colder temperatures?

tl;dr It's probably the opposite. In the three coldest races she placed above average in the respective disciplines. All of these results were also in the Top 5.

>Considerations
-considered all races categorized by FIS as either World Cup, Stage World Cup, World Championship or Olympic Games
-temperatures are from FIS' result PDFs
-19 different competitions (18 if you count the Tour de Ski climb as a normal 10 km F Mst) grouped into SP Qual, SP Final, 10 km, 15 km, Skiathlon, 20 km and 30 km for the plot
>Sprint
-only discipline in which she finished below 20th place
-no Sprint podium
-two failed qualifications: Ruka 2019 (40th) and Lenzerheide 2021 (34th)
-other reslts outside Top 25: Falun 2022 (Qual: 28th, Final: 25th)
-all of these races were close or above 0 °C
-the other Sprint results seem to be independent of the temperature
>10 km
-36 out of 67 races (68 with the Oberstdorf 2022 SP C Final DSQ)
-both the three warmest and coldest races had a length of 10 km
-warmest races: Oberstdorf 2021 10 km F Mst (10.7 °C), Oberstdorf 2021 10 km F (14.4 °C), Seefeld 2019 10 km C (13.1 °C); all 2nd place
-coldest races: Beitostolen 2022 10 km C (-18.1 °C, 3rd), Ruka 2021 10 km F Pursuit (-17.0, 2nd) and 10 km C (-18.7 °C, 1st)
-seems like she's performing better in extremely warm or cold temperatures, but three races each is a small sample size
-overall 10 km races have slight trend for worse results at higher temperatures
>Distance
-Top 5 in all races longer than 10 km regardless of temperature
-Almost identical conditions in two of the three 30 km races
-Oberstdorf 2021 30 km C Mst (5.7 °C, 3rd) and Seefeld 2019 30 km F Mst (5.6 °C; 3rd)

There's actually a good reason for it. Your body will keep some of the energy it has in reserve in case you really need it, like say you meet a gorilla that threatens to kill you unless you give him your wallet and phone. Adrenaline from that threat will then allow your body to go extra deep and use every single reserve you have left.

Now if you ingest sugar it tells your body that there's more energy coming and that it's ok to use more of the reserves because there's replacement energy on the pipeline. In fact you don't even have to eat the gel, just swirling something sugary in your mouth and spitting it out will trigger that response.

Had a few mediocre cards in a row, keep going 5-5 with the larger favorites coming through. Let's do better tonight. UFC 284 picks:

Favorites
Makhachev inside distance -115: I'm a huge Volkanovski fan but he's just too small and he's never fought an elite wrestler other than Mendes well past his prime. I think this one ends by choke in the 3rd or 4th. Islam will wear Alex down and eventually take his back and finish him.

Yair -180 vs Emmett: Emmett's power scares me a bit, but Yair should be able to use reach to control distance. He'll go to the body and legs early and often while Emmett headhunts. If Emmett doesn't get a finish inside 3 rounds Yair will win. Emmett also looked like a holocaust victim at the weigh in yesterday, no telling if his chin will be rehydrated.

JDM vs Brown over 1.5 rounds -160: Everyone expects a firefight but I see this as a more technical fight. Brown is so tall and long it will be a challenge for Jack to find range and land power. Might see some grappling from Jack, which is the MMA equivalent of running the ball in football. Eats up clock and we get to 7:30 at least.

Pedro-Bukauskas fight does NOT go the distance: Pedro has looked excellent since a long injury layoff, and Bukauskas is making his UFC return on short notice. Bukauskas gets hit a lot and has solid finishing instincts. Someone gets TKO'd.

Culibao-Baghdasaryan goes to decision -150: Not much analysis here, these guys aren't finishers at the UFC level and both are durable.
